doc.ContractDescription: IGF::CT::IGF EAPD-BIO.0118-15; E-048-2012/0-EP-03; HARRIS; PATENT LEGAL SERVICE (WONG)
TO DEFINE THE STRUCTURE AND RELATED TASKS THAT ARE REQUIRED TO ENSURE SMOOTH AND CONSISTENT DELIVERY OF TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO EXISTING AND FUTURE YOUTHBUILD GRANTEES.

THE REQUESTED FUNDING WILL BE USED TO SUPPORT THE ACTIVITIES OF TWO POSTDOCTORAL SCHOLARS WHO WILL PERFORM THE FOLLOWING RESEARCH AND ASSOCIATED ACTIVITIES WITH LUNAR ORBITER LASER ALTIMETER (LOLA) DATA AND OTHER PLANETARY LASER ALTIMETER DATA. THE LUNAR ORBITER LASER ALTIMETER (LOLA) INSTRUMENT IS A COMPONENT OF THE PAYLOAD ON THE LUNAR RECONNAISSANCE ORBITER (LRO) SPACECRAFT THAT IS PRESENTLY ORBITING THE MOON. LOLA HAS ACQUIRED A SIGNIFICANT QUANTITY OF DATA THAT IS ENABLING THE STUDY OF THE EVOLUTION OF THE LUNAR SURFACE AND INTERIOR. THE LOLA DATA ARE PROVIDING UNIQUE DATA ON THE STRUCTURE OF BASINS AND LARGE CARTERS THAT CAN BE USED TO HELP MODEL THEIR STRUCTURE AND MECHANICAL STRENGTH AT AND SINCE THE TIME OF FORMATION. THESE UNIQUE DATA PROVIDE A VIEW INTO THE OUTER LAYERS OF THE MOON'S CRUST, FROM WHICH WE CAN BEGIN TO UNDERSTAND THE EVOLUTION OF THE MOON SINCE ITS FORMATION 4 GA AGO. LUNAR HISTORY IS INFERRED FROM THE PROCESSES THAT SHAPE PLANETARY SURFACE, PARTICULARLY EARLY BOMBARDMENT. THANKS TO THE LACK OF AN ATMOSPHERE AND OCEAN AND THE ABSENCE OF SUBDUCTION THE EARLY SURFACE RECORD OF THE MOON IS EXTREMELY WELL PRESERVED. COMPARISON WITH OTHER BODIES IN THE SOLAR SYSTEM CAN BE USED TO UNDERSTAND HOW THE EARLY SOLAR SYSTEM EVOLVED TO ITS PRESENT STATE. SIMILAR DATA HAVE BEEN ACQUIRED OF BOTH MARS, WHICH IS FURTHER FROM THE SUN THAN EARTH, AND MERCURY, WHICH IS CLOSER TO THE SUN, AND THUS COMPARISONS OF THE LOLA DATA WITH THESE SIMILAR DATASETS WILL PROVIDE A UNIQUE VIEW OF THE INNER SOLAR SYSTEM. LOLA DATA ACQUIRED BY LRO WILL BE EDITED, APPROPRIATE CALIBRATIONS APPLIED, AND USED TO MODEL A VARIETY OF LUNAR FEATURES THAT WILL PROVIDE A UNIQUE DESCRIPTION OF THE LUNAR CRUST AND OUTER MANTLE. A RANGE OF CRATER AND BASIN SIZES WILL BE STUDIED TO OBTAIN DATA ON THE OUTER 300 KM OF THE MOON, THAT CAN BE COMPARED WITH SIMILAR ANALYSES OF THE BOTH MARS AND MERCURY. GRAVITY DATA, ALSO BEING ACQUIRED BY LRO, WILL BE USED IN CONJUNCTION WITH LOLA DATA TO OBTAIN IMPROVED ESTIMATES OF THE CRUSTAL THICKNESS OF THE MOON RESULTING FROM THE SIGNIFICANTLY MORE ACCURATE LUNAR TOPOGRAPHY. THIS NEW MODEL, WITH IMPROVED RESOLUTION, WILL BE A PRE-DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITY FOR THE GRAIL MISSION DUE FOR LAUNCH LATER IN 2011 THAT WILL PROVIDE A HIGH-RESOLUTION GRAVITY MODEL FOR USE WITH THE HIGH RESOLUTION TOPOGRAPHY OF LOLA. USING THE BEST AND MOST PRECISE LOLA TOPOGRAPHY DATA AN ATTEMPT WILL BE MADE TO RECOVER VARIOUS PARAMETERS THAT DESCRIBE THE ROTATIONAL STATE OF THE MOON. THE LUNAR PHYSICALLIBRATIONS AND TIDES CAUSE THE TOPOGRAPHY AT A GIVEN LOCATION TO APPEAR TO CHANGE WITH TIME IF THESE EFFECTS ARE NOT ACCOUNTED FOR OR MODELED CORRECTLY. THUS, ALTHOUGH SOME OF THESE EFFECTS ARE SMALL IN THE WAY THEY MODIFY THE APPARENT TOPOGRAPHY THE LOLA DATA CAN BE USED TO ESTIMATE THESE PARAMETERS BECAUSE THEY ARE GLOBAL IN PHASE AND MAGNITUDE. THE LOLA DATA CAN THUS PROVIDE AN INDEPENDENT ESTIMATION OF THE LIBRATION, ORIENTATION AND TIDAL DEFORMATION OF THE MOON FROMWHICH PARAMETERS DESCRIBING THE LUNAR INTERIOR, INCLUDING CORE SIZE AND MANTLE STRUCTURE CAN BE DETERMINED. MERCURY, LIKE THE MOON HAS A SURFACE THAT APPEARS TO HAVE RETAINED MUCH OF THE HISTORY OF ITS EARLY FORMATION AND SUBSEQUENT BOMBARDMENT. THUS, THE TOPOGRAPHIC, GRAVITY, AND CRUSTAL THICKNESS POWER SPECTRA OF THESE TWO BODIES WILL COMPARED AND STUDIED FOR UNDERSTANDING THE ORIGINS OF BOTH BODIES AND THE PLACE IN THE SOLAR SYSTEM. THESE INVESTIGATIONS WILL BE CONDUCTED IN COLLABORATION WITH COLLEAGUES AT THE NASA GODDARD SPACE FLIGHT CENTER. THE WORK AT MIT WILL BE CONDUCTED BY 2 POST DOCS UNDER THE DIRECT SUPERVISION OF THE PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR.

THE ASTRO-H MISSION, NOW UNDER DEVELOPMENT BY NASA'S GODDARD SPACE FLIGHT CENTER (GSFC) AND THE JAPANESE AEROSPACE EXPLORATION AGENCY (JAXA) FOR LAUNCH IN 2014, WILL BE THE PREMIER NEW X-RAY OBSERVATORY OF THIS DECADE. THE ASTRO-H SOFT X-RAY SPECTROMETER (SXS) WILL PROVIDE SPATIALLY RESOLVED SPECTROSCOPY WITH UNPRECEDENTED SPECTRAL RESOLUTION, AND WILL REVOLUTIONIZE THE STUDY OF EXTENDED X-RAY SOURCES RANGING FROM SUPERNOVA REMNANTS TO CLUSTERS OF GALAXIES. THE SXS WILL BE COMPLEMENTED ON ASTRO-H BY A WIDE-FIELD, SOFT X-RAY CCD IMAGER (SXI) AND A PAIR OF HARD X-RAY IMAGERS (HXI). IN CONSIDERATION OF NASA'S CRITICAL CONTRIBUTIONS TO ASTRO-H INSTRUMENTATION, INCLUDING KEY COMPONENTS OF THE SXS AS WELL AS X -RAY TELESCOPE (XRT) MIRRORS FOR THE SXS AND SXI, THE US SCIENTIFIC COMMUNITY WILL RECEIVE RIGHTS TO PROPOSE FOR A SIGNIFICANT FRACTION OF ASTRO-H OBSERVING TIME. IN ORDER TO ASSURE THE SCIENTIFIC QUALITY AND READY AVAILABILITY OF THESE DATA TO THE COMMUNITY, NASA'S GSFC HAS ALSO ASSUMED A LEADING ROLE IN COORDINATION OF GROUND AND FLIGHT CALIBRATION, AND IN DEVELOPMENT OF GROUND PROCESSING SOFTWARE FOR ALL INSTRUMENTS ON ASTRO-H. HERE MKI PROPOSES TO SUPPORT TO THE ASTRO-H TEAM AT GSFC AS IT PLANS CALIBRATION AND GROUND SOFTWARE FOR ASTRO-H. MKI'S UNIQUE QUALIFICATIONS FOR THIS ROLE, AND THE PROPOSED STATEMENT OF WORK, SCHEDULE AND BUDGET ARE DESCRIBED IN TURN.

THE FORMATION AND EVOLUTION OF A MAGNETIC DYNAMO IS AN INTEGRAL PART OF THE EVOLUTION OF LOW-MASS STARS AND THE BASIS FOR A WIDE VARIETY OF OBSERVABLE PHENOMENA. YET DESPITE DECADES OF STUDY, WE DO NOT HAVE A PREDICTIVE DYNAMO MODEL EVEN FOR THE BEST STUDIED CASE - THE SUN. A LIMITING FACTOR HAS BEEN THE DIFFICULTY IN DETERMINING KEY PHYSICAL PROPERTIES, SUCH AS DIFFERENTIAL ROTATION AND TURBULENT DIFFUSIVITY, IMPORTANT FOR UNDERSTANDING AND MODELING THE STELLAR DYNAMO. WE PROPOSE TO USE KEPLER'S SUPERB PHOTOMETRY TO MEASURE DIFFERENTIAL ROTATION AS WELL AS THE DECAY RATES OF SURFACE ACTIVE REGIONS (A PROXY FOR DIFFUSIVITY) FOR 235 KNOWN MEMBERS OF THE OPEN CLUSTERS NGC 6811 (1 GYR) AND NGC 6819 (2.5 GYR). OUR GROUP IS UNIQUELY SUITED TO STUDY THESE CLUSTERS DUE TO OUR EXTENSIVE GROUND-BASED PHOTOMETRIC/SPECTROSCOPIC CAMPAIGN TO IDENTIFY LOW-MASS MEMBERS OF THESE CLUSTERS. THE PROPOSED STUDY WILL MORE THAN TRIPLE THE EXISTING DIFFERENTIAL ROTATION MEASUREMENTS FOR DWARF STARS OVER A WIDE RANGE OF MASSES, WITH THE ADDED ADVANTAGES OF HAVING FIXED METALLICITY AND WELL DETERMINED AGES. THIS WORK WILL ALSO YIELD THE FIRST EXTENSIVE SURVEY OF MAGNETIC GROWTH AND DECAY RATES IN HOMOGENEOUS SAMPLES OF DWARFS. WE WILL ALSO EXPLORE THE FREQUENCY OF MAGNETIC GRAND MINIMA AT YOUNGER AGES. THIS WORK EXTENDS SIMILAR WORK ON THESE CLUSTERS STARTED IN CYCLE 2. THE ADDED CYCLE OF DATA WILL ALLOW US TO COMPARE CYCLE 4 AND CYCLE 2 DIFFERENTIAL ROTATION RESULTS, ALLOWING US TO BEGIN TO SEE EVOLUTION OF ACTIVE LATITUDES OVER DYNAMO CYCLES. STATISTICS ON MAGNETIC DECAY TIMESCALES AS A FUNCTION OF ACTIVE REGION SIZE, STELLAR MASS AND ROTATION WILL ALSO BE REFINED. OUR MEASUREMENTS WILL ADD IMPORTANT NEW CONSTRAINTS ON MAGNETIC DYNAMOS IN STARS, PERMITTING BETTER, MORE PHYSICALLY REALISTIC MODELS. FORM NRESS-

COMMUNITY INTEREST IN REMOTELY SENSED SOIL MOISTURE IS BASED MAINLY ON THE INFLUENCE OF SOIL MOISTURE ON HYDROLOGIC FLUXES. IT IS THROUGH THIS INFLUENCE, FOR EXAMPLE, THAT SOIL MOISTURE FINDS RELEVANCE IS CLIMATE MODELING (E.G. LATENT HEATING OF THE ATMOSPHERE), WATER RESOURCES MANAGEMENT (E.G. AGRICULTURAL WATER USE), AND CIVIL ENGINEERING (E.G. FLOOD RISK). THE ACTUAL QUANTITY OF SOIL MOISTURE, MEASURED FOR EXAMPLE AS A MASS OF WATER PER VOLUME OF SOIL, IS TYPICALLY OF LESS DIRECT INTEREST. THIS IS ESPECIALLY TRUE OF MICROWAVE ESTIMATES (E.G. RECENT PRODUCTS DERIVED FROM AMSR-E), WHICH MEASURE SHALLOW DEPTHS, AND THUS ARE NOT USEFUL FOR TRACKING TOTAL STORAGE CHANGE IN WATERSHEDS. MANY RECENTLY PUBLISHED ARTICLES COMPARING GROUND-MEASURED AND REMOTELY-ESTIMATED SOIL MOISTURE HAVE FOUND THAT BOTH MEASURES NEED TO FIRST BE SCALED AND CENTERED IN SOME WAY FOR COMPARISON, I.E. RELATIVE FLUCTUATIONS ARE MEASURED WELL, BUT SIGNIFICANT BIAS AND RANGE ISSUES REMAIN. COMPARING INDICES OF SOIL MOISTURE FORMED IN THESE WAYS IS USEFUL, BUT HERE WE PRESENT AN IDEA FOR TRYING TO GET MORE DIRECTLY AT THE INFORMATION CONTENT OF THE SATELLITE ESTIMATES WITH RESPECT TO THEIR RELATION TO HYDROLOGIC FLUXES. TO DO THIS, WE USE A CONDITIONAL AVERAGING METHOD IN WHICH PRECIPITATION MEASUREMENTS, CONDITIONALLY AVERAGED ACCORDING TO SOIL MOISTURE LEVEL, ESTIMATE THE DEPENDENCE OF DRAINAGE, RUNOFF AND EVAPOTRANSPIRATION ON SOIL MOISTURE. THE AVERAGING PROCESS RESULTS IN MOISTURE-OUTFLOW CURVES CHARACTERISTIC OF THE DOMINANT FLOW PROCESSES AND LAND SURFACE CHARACTERISTICS (E.G., SOIL AND VEGETATION). THIS CENTRAL IDEA HAS BEEN DEVELOPED AND PUBLISHED PREVIOUSLY FOR A RANGE OF APPLICATIONS INCLUDING SPATIAL AND TEMPORAL SCALING STUDIES AND MODEL PARAMETER ESTIMATION. HERE WE POSTULATE THAT HIGH QUALITY SATELLITE ESTIMATES OF SOIL MOISTURE, USED IN THE CONDITIONAL AVERAGING OF PRECIPITATION, WILL YIELD SIMILAR MOISTURE-OUTFLOW CURVES TO THOSE WE HAVE FOUND AT FIELD SITES: I.E., SIGMOIDAL RELATIONS THAT REFLECT STRESSED EVAPOTRANSPIRATION FOR DRY SOILS, ROUGHLY CONSTANT FLUX EQUAL TO POTENTIAL EVAPORATION MINUS CAPILLARY RISE FOR MODERATELY DRY SOILS, AND RAPID DRAINAGE FOR VERY WET SOILS. FURTHER WE POSTULATE THAT POOR QUALITY MOISTURE ESTIMATES WILL YIELD FLATTER, OR LESS INFORMATIVE, MOISTURE-OUTFLOW CURVES, AND THAT THEY WILL EXPLAIN LESS OF THE PRECIPITATION VARIABILITY. WE QUANTIFY THIS WITH AN INDEX OF SOIL MOISTURE INFORMATION. HERE WE WILL DEVELOP AND APPLY THESE IDEAS IN RESPONSE TO THE SOLICITED RESEARCH FOCUS 2.2: SATELLITE VALIDATION APPROACHES, WHICH CALLS FOR MOVING BEYOND COMPARING A TIME SERIES OF SATELLITE DERIVED SOIL MOISTURE WITH ONE OR MORE IN SITU POINT OBSERVATIONS. THE WORK PLAN IS TO UTILIZE THE NLDAS AND GLDAS GRIDDED PRECIPITATION PRODUCTS AND AT LEAST THREE SOIL MOISTURE ESTIMATES DERIVED FROM AMSR-E (THE NASA PRODUCT, THE LPRM PRODUCT, AND THE NEW JONES AND KIMBALL PRODUCT), AND, DEPENDING ON DATA RELEASES, THE SMOS PRODUCTS. PRELIMINARY ANALYSIS SHOW SIGNIFICANT DIFFERENCES IN THE VARIOUS PRODUCTS CAPABILITY TO RECREATE GROUND-BASED MEASURES OF HOW HYDROLOGIC FLUXES DEPEND ON MOISTURE. BECAUSE THE APPROACH REQUIRES ONLY PRECIPITATION AND THE SATELLITE DERIVED MOISTURE PRODUCT, WE CAN EVALUATE THE PRODUCTS OVER A WIDE RANGE OF SURFACE AND CLIMATE CONDITIONS, I.E., WE ARE NOT RESTRICTED TO A FEW FIELD SITES.

doc.ContractDescription: WE WILL USE TWO NEWLY-AVAILABLE DATASETS, EACH WITH UNIQUE STRENGTHS, TO EXPLORE THE IONOSPHERE OF MARS. THE FIRST DATASET IS THE COLLECTION OF IONOSPHERIC ELECTRON DENSITY PROFILES ACQUIRED BY THE MARINER 9 RADIO OCCULTATION EXPERIMENT IN 1971-2. WE HAVE REDISCOVERED THESE ON ARCHIVED MICROFILM AND ARE IN THE PROCESS OF CONVERTING THEM TO USABLE DIGITAL FILES. THESE PROFILES EXTEND TO 400 KM, MUCH HIGHER THAN THE CORRESPONDING MGS PROFILES, ENABLING STUDIES OF THE HIGH ALTITUDE IONOSPHERE, AND COVER A MASSIVE DUST STORM, ENABLING STUDIES OF LOWER-UPPER ATMOSPHERE COUPLING. THE SECOND DATASET CONTAINS IONOSPHERIC ELECTRON DENSITIES FROM MARSIS ON MARS EXPRESS, BOTH LOCAL DENSITIES AT THE SPACECRAFT (275-1250 KM) AND REMOTELY-SENSED DENSITIES AT LOWER ALTITUDES (120-275 KM). THESE DATA CROSS THE IONOPAUSE (TYPICALLY 400 KM, BUT HIGHLY VARIABLE) AND THEIR RAPID SAMPLING CADENCE REVEALS HORIZONTAL AND TEMPORAL GRADIENTS IN UNPRECEDENTED DETAIL. NEVERTHELESS, SEVERAL UNUSUAL FEATURES, PARTICULARLY AT THE 275 KM TRANSITION BETWEEN THE TWO DATA TYPES, DEMONSTRATE A CLEAR NEED FOR A CAREFUL COMPARISON OF MARSIS ELECTRON DENSITIES AGAINST THOSE MEASURED BY THE WELL-CHARACTERIZED TECHNIQUE OF RADIO OCCULTATIONS. WE SHALL FIRST MAKE THE MARINER 9 IONOSPHERIC DATASET PUBLICLY AVAILABLE (TASK A: ARCHIVING THE MARINER 9 ELECTRON DENSITY PROFILES). NEXT, WE SHALL STUDY THIS DATASET BEARING IN MIND THE MANY DISCOVERIES MADE AT MARS SINCE THE MARINER 9 INSTRUMENT TEAM LAST ANALYZED IT (TASK B: SCIENTIFIC INTERPRETATION OF THE MARINER 9 ELECTRON DENSITY PROFILES). FINALLY, WE SHALL COMPARE SEVERAL SYNTHESIZED REPRESENTATIONS OF IONOSPHERIC ELECTRON DENSITIES THAT HAVE BEEN PUBLISHED BY THE MARSIS TEAM TO MARINER 9 AND MGS RADIO OCCULTATION ELECTRON DENSITY PROFILES (TASK C: COMPARISON OF MARSIS AND RADIO OCCULTATION IONOSPHERIC MEASUREMENTS). AT THE CONCLUSION OF THIS PROJECT, WE EXPECT TO HAVE DEPOSITED A VALUABLE DATASET INTO NASA'S PERMANENT ARCHIVES, ENSURING ITS AVAILABILITY TO FUTURE GENERATIONS, TO HAVE USED IT TO STUDY FEATURES OF THE IONOSPHERE OF MARS THAT ARE NOT ACCESSIBLE TO CURRENT DATASETS, SUCH AS THE TOPSIDE IONOSPHERE AND THE RESPONSE TO A MASSIVE DUST STORM, AND TO HAVE COMPARED TWO TYPES OF MARSIS ELECTRON DENSITY MEASUREMENTS AGAINST INDEPENDENT RADIO OCCULTATION MEASUREMENTS, INCLUDING PROFILES THAT SPAN THE TRANSITION REGION BETWEEN MARSIS DATA TYPES.

THIS PROPOSAL WILL SUPPORT SWOT AND AIRSWOT IN THE AREAS OF COASTAL OCEANOGRAPHY AND ITS INTERACTIONS WITH ESTUARY WITH A PARTICULAR FOCUS ON HIGH RESOLUTION MODELING, DATA ASSIMILATION AND REAL-TIME FORECASTING APPLICATIONS. WHILE SWOT IS PLANNING TO PRODUCE A SWATH OF ELEVATION MEASUREMENTS OVER LAND SURFACE WATERS AND OVER THE OCEAN WATER SURFACE WITH THE GOAL OF MAKING A TRANSFORMATIONAL IMPACT IN TERRESTRIAL HYDROLOGY AND BREAKTHROUGHS IN MAPPING OCEAN SURFACE TOPOGRAPHY, RESPECTIVELY, HOW TO REFINE THE MISSION DESIGN AND MAXIMIZE THE SCIENCE RETURN IN THE COASTAL OCEAN AND ESTUARY STILL REMAINS LESS WELL-DEFINED. COASTAL OCEANS AND ESTUARIES LINK ELEVATION CHANGES BETWEEN LAND SURFACE WATERS AND OPEN OCEAN. WITH THE EXTENSIVE OBSERVING NETWORKS IN THE COASTAL OCEANS AND ESTUARIES, STRATEGIES AND TECHNIQUES FOR CALIBRATION AND VALIDATION OF SWOT AND AIRSWOT MEASUREMENTS CAN BE DEVELOPED, TESTED AND REFINED. THE PROPOSED OCEAN AND ESTUARY OFF THE US WEST COAST IS A NATURAL LABORATORY TO ACCOMPLISH THE FOLLOWING OBJECTIVES: 1) TO CHARACTERIZE THE SPATIAL AND TEMPORAL VARIABILITY OF THE COASTAL OCEAN AND ESTUARY 2) TO DEVELOP COASTAL AND ESTUARY DATA PRODUCTS USING 3D DYNAMICAL MODELS AND DATA ASSIMILATION 3) TO STUDY THE INTERACTIONS BETWEEN THE COASTAL OCEAN AND ESTUARY AND PREPARE SWOT FOR COASTAL/ESTUARY FORECASTING APPLICATIONS THE PI OF THIS PROPOSAL (Y. CHAO) HAS EXTENSIVE EXPERIENCES IN COASTAL OCEAN MODELING, DATA ASSIMILATION AND FORECASTING APPLICATIONS. THE PROPOSED MODELING, DATA ASSIMILATION AND FORECASTING SYSTEMS ARE EITHER DEVELOPED OR BEING DEVELOPING, LEVERAGING FUNDING FROM NASA AND OTHER FEDERAL AGENCIES. THE PROPOSED EFFORT WILL BE CLOSELY COORDINATED WITH THE SWOT PROJECT AND SDT MEMBERS. A SWOT/AIRSWOT TECHNOLOGIST (D. MOLLER) HAS BEEN IDENTIFIED AS A COLLABORATOR. THE COMBINED EXPERTISE WILL BE UNIQUE IN PROVIDING GUIDANCE TO THE SWOT PROJECT IN THE AREAS OF MEASUREMENT REQUIREMENTS, PRODUCT DEFINITION, GEOPHYSICAL ERROR SOURCES, ALGORITHM DEVELOPMENT, CALIBRATION, VALIDATION, AND SCIENTIFIC APPLICATIONS. THE PROPOSED NUMERICAL MODEL SIMULATIONS WILL BE INTEGRATED WITH THE SWOT SIMULATOR IN ORDER TO ASSESS THE PERFORMANCE OF SWOT DATA ASSIMILATION, CONDUCT OBSERVING SYSTEM SENSITIVITY EXPERIMENTS (OSSES), AND EXPLORE SCIENCE/MISSION TRADE-OFFS FOR SPATIAL RESOLUTION, TEMPORAL SAMPLING, INSTRUMENT ACCURACY AND CORRECTION ALGORITHMS. USING ADVANCED DATA ASSIMILATION TECHNIQUES, WE PLAN TO DEFINE/DEVELOP/TEST AND PRODUCE A HIGHER LEVEL DATA PRODUCT USING BOTH MULTI-SATELLITE DATA SETS (E.G., SEA SURFACE TEMPERATURE, SEA SURFACE SALINITY, BACKSCATTER INTENSITY FROM SWOT) AND LAND-BASED HIGH-FREQUENCY (HF) RADARS AS WELL AS IN SITU MEASUREMENTS (E.G., MOORINGS, PROFILING FLOATS, GLIDERS). THE DATA LATENCY IN THE COASTAL OCEAN AND ESTUARY WILL BE EVALUATED AND ITS POSSIBLE IMPACT ON FORECAST APPLICATIONS WILL BE QUANTIFIED.
